he 0th, 3rd, and 4th stocks for a total of 5 + 2 + 3 = 10.\nNext year, sell all three stocks for a total of 8 + 3 + 5 = 16.\nThe profit you made is 16 - 10 = 6.\nIt can be shown that the maximum profit you can make is 6.\n\nExample 2:\n\nInput: present = [2,2,5], future = [3,4,10], budget = 6\nOutput: 5\nExplanation: The only possible way to maximize your profit is to:\nBuy the 2nd stock, and make a profit of 10 - 5 = 5.\nIt can be shown that the maximum profit you can make is 5.\n\nExample 3:\n\nInput: present = [3,3,12], future = [0,3,15], budget = 10\nOutput: 0\nExplanation: One possible way to maximize your profit is to:\nBuy the 1st stock, and make a profit of 3 - 3 = 0.\nIt can be shown that the maximum profit you can make is 0.\n\n \nConstraints:\n\nn == present.length == future.length\n1 <= n <= 1000\n0 <= present[i], future[i] <= 100\n0 <= budget <= 1000\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def maximumProfit(self, present: List[int], future: List[int], budget: int) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def maximumProfit(self, present: List[int], future: List[int], budget: int) -> int:\n        # Calculate the profit for each stock if bought today\n        profits = [(future[i] - present[i], present[i]) for i in range(len(present)) if future[i] > present[i]]\n        \n        # Sort the stocks by their present price\n        profits.sort(key=lambda x: x[1])\n        \n        # Initialize a DP array where dp[b] is the maximum profit with budget b\n        dp = [0] * (budget + 1)\n        \n        # Iterate over each stock\n        for profit, cost in profits:\n            # Update the dp array from right to left to avoid using the same stock multiple times\n            for b in range(budget, cost - 1, -1):\n                dp[b] = max(dp[b], dp[b - cost] + profit)\n        \n        # The maximum profit will be in dp[budget]\n        return dp[budget]\n```\n\nThis solution uses dynamic programming to solve the problem. It first calculates the potential profit for each stock and filters out stocks that do not make a profit. It then sorts these stocks by their present price and uses a DP array to keep track of the maximum profit that can be achieved with a given budget. The DP array is updated in reverse order to ensure that each stock is only considered once.", "estimated_date": 1653782400000}